    "# When things go wrong: understanding errors\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/fallen_me.jpeg\n",
    ":alt: a character has fallen on the ground and is dizzy. Next to them is a smoking laptop.\n",
    ":width: 30%\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "However hard you work to make everything alright, you will encounter errors. In this section, I list common errors I have seen and how to deal with them. This is not, by any way, exhaustive. In the last part I will discuss a bit how to deal with the unexpected, how to report issues, and how to get help."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4eff3355-b7ad-4587-8d71-ab1f4ec57abe",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Finding useful errors / finding errors useful\n",
    "\n",
    "The first step to understanding, and hopefully fixing, errors is to be able to find and identify errors. The first place you want to look at is the logger in the main window. Qudi modules are able to communicate with it and output there error messages. Actually, we can print one right now! If you execute the following code snippet:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "26833fa0-9ca2-4c0a-9d83-837206ccd073",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "instream_dummy.log.error(\"Hey, I am an error message!\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3dc25509-05f4-454a-8d3c-5a93790b82f3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You will see the following message in the logger:\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/error_message_main_window.png\n",
    ":width: 80%\n",
    "\n",
    "The error message we just printed!\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "You can double click on the message to copy and paste it to report it, or look for solutions online for example. You can see that Qudi tells you which Python module produced the message and at which time. This kind of error message happens when the person that coded the module anticipated that an error could occur and decided to alert the user. This means it is up to the programmer to make the error message useful in helping you fix the error!\n",
    "\n",
    "If you have a look at the terminal in which Qudi is running, you will see that the error message also appears there, albeit with less informations available.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/error_message_terminal.png\n",
    ":width: 30%\n",
    "\n",
    "The error message in the terminal\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "This redundancy is useful if the main window comes to crash for example. The last place where you can find errors is in the log file (see [](log-viewer) section to locate this file). Always with our example, Qudi outputed the following line in my file when I ran it:\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "2025-12-14 16:31:40 error qudi.hardware.dummy.data_instream_dummy.InStreamDummy Hey, I am an error message!\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "As you can see, we retrieve the same pieces of information as in the main window. This is also useful if the main window becomes unavailable, or if you closed it before reporting the error."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "51f63575-2686-41a6-a0de-f2f5b0463db8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A second kind of error message that you can find is a Python exception report. This typically happens when the person who coded the modules you are using did not anticipate an error, but Qudi was able to catch it.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{warning}\n",
    "When a Python error happens the flow of the program execution is cut, sometimes abruptly, which means it is harder to ensure that the program is in a consistent state. It might be safer in this case to restart the execution from scratch!\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "```{note} For advanced users, and users who will code their own modules.\n",
    "Qudi is rather good at catching errors. However, some error will fail silently and can be hard to debug. This is especially the case when some code is not running in the main thread. For these specific cases, the easiest solution I have found for now is to print regularly bits of informations in the logger to detect errors.\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Although this is probably something you already know, it is worth spending one minute to remind you how to read a Python error. First, let's trigger an error with our current configuration, using the `instream_dummy` hardware. This hardware will refuse to read data if an acquisition is not running. Let's try the following code snippet:"
   ]
  },

      "\u001b[0;31mRuntimeError\u001b[0m: Unable to read data.      "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Qudi IPython kernel disconnected from local module service.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "time_series_reader_logic.stop_reading() # make sure no acquisition is running. \n",
    "instream_dummy.read_data(10) # read 10 data points"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b37ccbed-28c2-440a-baa3-b07f24fdc9b4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Everything exploded! Since we are running code in a notebook, two errors are reported. One is local to the notebook (the first one) and you can ignore it, and the other corresponds to the error in Qudi (you can see that it mention a `Remote Traceback`, this is because the Python instance that runs Qudi is considered a remote excecution thread by the notebook). If Qudi had caught this error in a module (for example if your logic module was flawed), it would have only printed the last bit in the log viewer. Let's try to go through this error to learn to read it.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/python_error.png\n",
    ":width: 100%\n",
    "\n",
    "The error message with flashy colors. Everything is better in flashy colors. :)\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dd008952-452b-4a56-ac27-4d5775836d06",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The error should be read from bottom to top. The first, and maybe most important bit is the error name and the error message, highlighted in light blue. The error name gives you an idea of the kind of error that happened. Python provides [a set of built-in exceptions](https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html), and developpers are free to add their own. For example, a developper wanting to report an error related to a division by zero might use [`ZeroDivisionError`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html#ZeroDivisionError). The message is a hint left by the developper to understand the origin and reason for the error to happen, and maybe help you fix it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1dcc33eb-3b3e-413d-adb2-6e750483b174",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The second part of the error is the **traceback**. This is the list of successive calls that led to the error. The very last one is said to be on the top of the stack. A call report tells you in which file, line, and function the executed code can be found (in dark blue, orange, and green respectively). The code making the call is reported below in purple in by illustration.\n",
    "\n",
    "As you can see the last call includes a `raise` statement, whose function is... to raise an error and interrupt the code execution. This call happened because of the call above, etc. If we had not deliberately triggered this error, we might use the traceback to track the origin of the error and perhaps fix it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bd75bd6b-f2b2-4b89-aa2c-b31964dd0d7f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Configuration file errors"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "18dc9398-a669-411f-8e0d-7a641d2d286c",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "In this section, I list some common errors that can be linked to configuration files\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/wrong_configuration.jpeg\n",
    ":alt: A character is trying to connect two pieces of a puzzle that cannot fit together\n",
    ":width: 30%\n",
    "\n",
    "Connectors must match the expected interfaces.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "55fcd620-caa7-4be0-b1bf-3be4212890e8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Wrong interfaces\n",
    "\n",
    "As we discussed before, in Qudi the modules interact between each other through the defined interfaces. If you try to connect a module that does not implement the right interface, Qudi will yell at you. For example, if I try to connect a module that does not implement the `DataInStreamInterface`, I will get the following error:\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "2025-12-14 18:20:37 error qudi.Qudi Unable to activate autostart module \"time_series_gui\":\n",
    "Traceback (most recent call last):\n",
    "  File \"[...]qudi/core/application.py\", line 292, in _start_startup_modules\n",
    "    self.module_manager.activate_module(module)\n",
    "  File \"[...]qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 208, in activate_module\n",
    "    self._modules[module_name].activate()\n",
    "  File \"[...]qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 540, in activate\n",
    "    module.activate()\n",
    "  File \"[...]qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 543, in activate\n",
    "    self._connect()\n",
    "  File \"[...]qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 763, in _connect\n",
    "    self._instance.connect_modules(module_connections)\n",
    "  File \"[...]qudi/core/module.py\", line 416, in connect_modules\n",
    "    conn.connect(target)\n",
    "  File \"[...]qudi/core/connector.py\", line 109, in connect\n",
    "    raise RuntimeError(\n",
    "RuntimeError: Module \"<qudi.hardware.dummy.switch_dummy.SwitchDummy(0x559b9a2c4d70) at 0x7fdc9c0d7ec0>\" connected to connector \"streamer\" does not implement interface \"DataInStreamInterface\".\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "This is a standard error display, the error is rather explicit, we need a hardware that implements `DataInStreamInterface`!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f712f41d-e554-4a95-8685-a88ebf30106d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Module not existing\n",
    "\n",
    "If you try to load a module that does not exist (for example because of a typo), Qudi will be unhappy. For example, if I try to load `switches.switch_dummy.SwitchDummy` (the correct module name would be `dummy.switch_dummy.SwitchDummy`):\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "2025-12-14 18:24:10 error qudi.Qudi Unhandled qudi exception:\n",
    "Traceback (most recent call last):\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 208, in activate_module\n",
    "    self._modules[module_name].activate()\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 508, in activate\n",
    "    self._load()\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 720, in _load\n",
    "    mod = importlib.import_module(f'qudi.{self._base}.{self._module}')\n",
    "  File \"[...]/python3.10/importlib/__init__.py\", line 126, in import_module\n",
    "    return _bootstrap._gcd_import(name[level:], package, level)\n",
    "  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 1050, in _gcd_import\n",
    "  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 1027, in _find_and_load\n",
    "  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 992, in _find_and_load_unlocked\n",
    "  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 241, in _call_with_frames_removed\n",
    "  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 1050, in _gcd_import\n",
    "  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 1027, in _find_and_load\n",
    "  File \"<frozen importlib._bootstrap>\", line 1004, in _find_and_load_unlocked\n",
    "ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'qudi.hardware.switch'\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Here also, the error is rather explicit, `qudi.hardware.switch` does not exist."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e9e2aa7-68a7-402f-8c95-0cd25ffd0923",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "### YAML errors\n",
    "\n",
    "YAML is a tricky file format to work with. It is especially fragile to indentation errors, and even experienced developpers can have issues using it.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/yaml.jpeg\n",
    ":width: 30%\n",
    ":alt: A character is shaking at the thought of writing YAML\n",
    "\n",
    "The cry of the postdoc condemned to write YAML, circa 2025.\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "For example, if I sneak [a tabulation character](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tab_key) in my configuration file, Qudi will crash trying to load the file.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "2025-12-14 18:33:31 error qudi.Qudi Invalid qudi configuration file specified. Falling back to default config.\n",
    "Traceback (most recent call last):\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/application.py\", line 134, in __init__\n",
    "    self.configuration.load(config_file, set_default=True)\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/config/config.py\", line 157, in load\n",
    "    config = self._load(file_path)\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/config/file_handler.py\", line 42, in _load\n",
    "    return yaml_load(cls._relative_to_absolute_path(path))\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/util/yaml.py\", line 260, in yaml_load\n",
    "    data = YAML().load(f)\n",
    "  File \"[...]/ruamel/yaml/main.py\", line 453, in load\n",
    "    return constructor.get_single_data()\n",
    "  File \"[...]/ruamel/yaml/constructor.py\", line 117, in get_single_data\n",
    "    node = self.composer.get_single_node()\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 706, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser.get_single_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 724, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_document\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 775, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 889, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_mapping_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 775, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 889, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_mapping_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 775, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 889, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_mapping_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 775, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 891, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._compose_mapping_node\n",
    "  File \"_ruamel_yaml.pyx\", line 904, in ruamel.yaml.clib._ruamel_yaml.CParser._parse_next_event\n",
    "ruamel.yaml.scanner.ScannerError: while scanning for the next token\n",
    "found character that cannot start any token\n",
    "  in \"/home/klafyvel/Documents/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/exercise_1.cfg\", line 24, column 5\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "As you can see, the error tells me which line and column are offending.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{tip}\n",
    "To avoid issues with tabulation characters, I advise configuring your text editor to make it automatically replace tabulation characters by four spaces.\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "To avoid having to deal with YAML, Qudi provides an experimental graphical editor for configuration files, accessible from the main window. The interface is rather explicit, and you can try to play with it if you are curious.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/config_editor.png\n",
    ":width: 70%\n",
    "\n",
    "The experimental configuration editor.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c0b51d60-a4e4-4df0-9afc-b6c6cda8ad46",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Connectivity errors"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dc6c2746-b286-4e02-8f2c-6f02346ee9c4",
   "metadata": {
    "jp-MarkdownHeadingCollapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "I briefly mentionned in the section on configuration the existence of [remote modules](https://ulm-iqo.github.io/qudi-core/design_concepts/remote_modules.html). Connectivity error can also concern local modules. You will obviously encouter errors if the hardware you are trying to access is not connected. An error that I have often seen in the lab is having multiple Qudi instances running. This is often due to people thinking they closed a previous instance of Qudi by clicking on the red cross on the top-right of the main window. This does not close Qudi and can lead to errors. Close Qudi instances by using the {kbd}`File > Quit qudi` menu in the main window preferably, or by closing the terminal in case QUdi crashed (but be aware that this is an extreme measure, and will not go through the usual extinction procedure).\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/too_many_qudi.jpeg\n",
    ":alt: A character has been submersed by little Qudi logos. only his thumb up is emerging.\n",
    ":width: 30%\n",
    "\n",
    "Multiple Qudi instances running in parallel will interfere with one another.\n",
    "```\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b6721147-0cdf-49c2-834d-a99370b3271c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It is probably rather clear why when the network is not working, you might have errors if you rely on it! To diagnose this kind of problems, you might try to visit a website if your network is supposed to be connected to the internet, verify that ethernet cables are connected, etc. Note that when you connect to a Qudi instance running on another computer, there might be issues when Qudi is closed on the main computer but is kept running on the remote computer. One solution is to close both Qudi instances, then starting the remote Qudi instance and finally the local Qudi instance.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/network_failure.jpeg\n",
    ":alt: A character is perplexed by a knot of ethernet cables.\n",
    ":width: 30%\n",
    "\n",
    "If you rely on hardware accessed through the network, you are dependent on the network working.\n",
    "```\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ce19f142-79bc-498b-b606-aa5b08df42a5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Coding errors"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "899da69d-c52b-4687-8c1b-e156261f654e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Although a lot of care has been put in the source code of the modules we use, we do encouter bugs from time to time. A smoking gun is typically Python errors originating from the source code.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/a_bug.jpeg\n",
    ":alt: A character is perplexed by a giant insect.\n",
    ":width: 30%\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "For example, if I sneak a `1 / 0` in the `on_activate` method of a module, I will get two errors.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "2025-12-14 19:24:21 error qudi.hardware.dummy.data_instream_dummy.InStreamDummy Exception during activation:\n",
    "Traceback (most recent call last):\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/module.py\", line 309, in __activation_callback\n",
    "    self.on_activate()\n",
    "  File \"[...]/src/qudi/hardware/dummy/data_instream_dummy.py\", line 313, in on_activate\n",
    "    1 / 0\n",
    "ZeroDivisionError: division by zero\n",
    "2025-12-14 19:24:21 error qudi.Qudi Unable to activate autostart module \"time_series_gui\":\n",
    "Traceback (most recent call last):\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 569, in activate\n",
    "    self._instance.module_state.activate()\n",
    "  File \"[...]/fysom/__init__.py\", line 299, in fn\n",
    "    raise Canceled(\n",
    "fysom.Canceled: Cannot trigger event activate because the onbeforeactivate handler returns False\n",
    "\n",
    "The above exception was the direct cause of the following exception:\n",
    "\n",
    "Traceback (most recent call last):\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/application.py\", line 292, in _start_startup_modules\n",
    "    self.module_manager.activate_module(module)\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 208, in activate_module\n",
    "    self._modules[module_name].activate()\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 540, in activate\n",
    "    module.activate()\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 540, in activate\n",
    "    module.activate()\n",
    "  File \"[...]/qudi/core/modulemanager.py\", line 571, in activate\n",
    "    raise RuntimeError(f'Failed to activate {self.module_base} module \"{self.name}\"!') from e\n",
    "RuntimeError: Failed to activate hardware module \"instream_dummy\"!\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "The second error corresponds to the GUI module failing to initialize because of another error, that corresponds to the module manager of Qudi failing to initialize the fake hardware module, which I tempered with. The first error is the actual error I introduced. Here the error is quite explicit, we have a division by zero and Python tells us where this occured.\n",
    "\n",
    "A very common programmation bug is one that we already encountered in the [](#scripting) section. When dealing with complex objects, typically Numpy arrays, obtained over the network, `netobtain` statements might be mising."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5bb042d7-03c1-456b-99cb-7dd440b6ea3c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## I have found an error, what do I do?\n",
    "\n",
    "We spent a good amount of time exploring some Qudi errors. Where do we go from there?\n",
    "\n",
    "### Trying to fix it yourself\n",
    "\n",
    "An appealing solution is to be able to fix the error by yourself. Some strategies include:\n",
    "* Finding a solution from the error message,\n",
    "* Restarting Qudi,\n",
    "* Clearing status variables: remember that they store the internal state between different runs of Qudi. Unfortunately, this can involve corrupted states. Check the [](#status-variables) section if you are unsure how to proceed.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Documenting the error\n",
    "\n",
    "Wether or not you are able to fix the issue yourself, it is useful to document it.\n",
    "1. Collect as much information on the error as you can. This includes the procedure to reproduce the error, the error message(s), screenshots, log files, any observation you can have on the situation (*use your experimentalist feelings!*)\n",
    "2. **Write it down**, for example in a labbook. It is best if the procedure is standardized in your group.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{important}\n",
    "Please, include the error messages **as text**. A screenshot of an error message is very impractical to work with because it can be hard to read and it is not searchable easily. Taking a picture of the screen with your phone is even worse because it potentially add a Moir pattern on the image. :(\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### Finding help\n",
    "\n",
    "Once you have an error well documented, and if you are not able to fix it yourself, you are ready to look for help. \n",
    "* Check the documentation,\n",
    "* Ask your colleagues,\n",
    "* You can also use [the official Qudi forum](https://github.com/Ulm-IQO/qudi-core/discussions).\n",
    "\n",
    "Asking for help is not necessarily easy, especially if you are not used to do that. As you will likely ask for help via text, you might be interested in these guides for asking help on computer-related problems:\n",
    "* [The XY problem](https://xyproblem.info/)\n",
    "* [Stackoverflow: how do I ask a good question?](https://stackoverflow.com/help/how-to-ask)\n",
    "* [How To Ask Questions The Smart Way](http://catb.org/~esr/faqs/smart-questions.html)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "61c767a4-fe6c-4ec1-a19c-6ea44f9e810d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Interactive activity: let's write a logic module\n",
    "\n",
    "The goal of this interactive section is to make you manipulate many aspects of Qudi. We will write a logic module and make it do several common actions. The final logic will be completely useless, but hopefully the different steps involved will be useful to make you understand the mechanisms involved. \n",
    "\n",
    "This is thought as a challenge with increasing levels of difficulty. The higher levels depend on you successfully clearing the lower levels.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{tip}\n",
    "If you are reading the notes without following the lecture, level 2 will be difficult (you need a hardware running on another computer of the network). You can try nonetheless and find a friend to test your solution!\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fe1ffed4-da79-4e0c-bd4f-fca9824b9670",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Level 0: Let's **not** write a logic module \n",
    "\n",
    "We are going to play at controlling a fake scanning laser. You can start with the following configuration:\n",
    "\n",
    "```yaml\n",
    "global:\n",
    "    # list of modules to load when starting\n",
    "    startup_modules: [time_series_gui, excitation_scanner_gui]\n",
    "    # Server port for serving the active qudi module namespace locally (localhost).\n",
    "    # Used by e.g. the Qudi jupyter kernel.\n",
    "    namespace_server_port: 18861\n",
    "    # Save data to daily data sub-directories by default\n",
    "    daily_data_dirs: True\n",
    "    force_remote_calls_by_value: True\n",
    "gui:\n",
    "    time_series_gui:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'time_series.time_series_gui.TimeSeriesGui'\n",
    "        options:\n",
    "            use_antialias: True  # optional, set to False if you encounter performance issues\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            _time_series_logic_con: time_series_reader_logic\n",
    "    excitation_scanner_gui:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'excitation_scanner.excitation_gui.ScanningExcitationGui'\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            excitation_logic: excitation_scanner_logic\n",
    "logic:\n",
    "    time_series_reader_logic:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'time_series_reader_logic.TimeSeriesReaderLogic'\n",
    "        options:\n",
    "            max_frame_rate: 20  # optional (default: 20Hz)\n",
    "            channel_buffer_size: 1048576  # optional (default: 1MSample)\n",
    "            max_raw_data_bytes: 1073741824  # optional (default: 1GB)\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            streamer: process_control_time_series\n",
    "    excitation_scanner_logic:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'scanning_excitation_spectroscopy.ScanningExcitationLogic'\n",
    "        options:\n",
    "            beep: True # default\n",
    "            watchdog_repeat_time_ms: 500 # default\n",
    "            save_idle_to_global_metadata: True # save the current idle value to global metadata\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            scanner: excitation_scanner_hardware\n",
    "hardware:\n",
    "    excitation_scanner_hardware:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'tutorial.laser.ExcitationScannerTutorial'\n",
    "    process_control:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'tutorial.process_control.ProcessControlTutorial'\n",
    "    process_control_time_series:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'interfuse.process_value_to_datainstream_interfuse.ProcessDataStream'\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            process: process_control\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "If you scan the frequencies, you should find a molecule!"

   "source": [
    "## Level 1: A logic module\n",
    "\n",
    "The idle frequency of `excitation_scanner_hardware` is actually flawed! The frequency we read has an offset with respect to the real frequency. This means that if we find a maximum and send the laser there, we won't be at the actual maximum. To fix this annoying issue, your task is to write a logic that has a single method to optimize the frequency.\n",
    "\n",
    "````{exercise}\n",
    ":label: level1\n",
    "\n",
    "Now that we know how to interact with our modules, write a Logic module that has a function to\n",
    "1. Scan specified range of frequencies using the `excitation_scanner_logic`,\n",
    "2. Find the maximum of the data, its frequency $f_0$, and the FWHM.\n",
    "3. Scan step by step a region [$f_0$-6FWHM, $f_0$+6FWHM] by setting manually the idle frequency of the `excitation_scanner_logic`. For each of these steps, record the fluorescence by probing the `\"APD\"` channel of the `process_control` module.\n",
    "4. Set the `excitation_scanner_logic` idle frequency to the frequency of the actual maximum.\n",
    "````\n",
    "\n",
    "You can use the following template to get started. Create the file `src/qudi/logic/frequency_optimize.py` and paste it.\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "import time\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "from qudi.core.connector import Connector\n",
    "from qudi.core.module import LogicBase\n",
    "from qudi.interface.process_control_interface import ProcessValueInterface\n",
    "from qudi.logic.scanning_excitation_spectroscopy import ScanningExcitationLogic\n",
    "\n",
    "class FrequencyOptimizeLogic(LogicBase):\n",
    "    _scanner = Connector(name='scanner_logic', interface=ScanningExcitationLogic)\n",
    "    _process = Connector(name='process_hardware', interface=ProcessValueInterface)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def on_activate(self):\n",
    "        # do you need something here?\n",
    "        pass\n",
    "\n",
    "    def on_deactivate(self):\n",
    "        # do you need something here?\n",
    "        pass\n",
    "\n",
    "    def optimize_frequency(self, fstart, fstop, fstep):\n",
    "        # You DO need things there!\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Once you have added your logic to the configuration, use the cell below to run your logic!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "fd5c0331-b2fd-4e18-b28f-c9bac32b8f52",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Someting along the line of frequency_optimize_logic.optimize_frequency(-10e9, -7e9, 50e6)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea8b335e-e31d-4689-beb1-bb6c5e78aa02",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Hints:\n",
    "* Don't forget the parentheses when calling the connectors: `self._scanner().something` and not `self._scanner.something`\n",
    "* Numpy has many useful functions, such as [`argmax`](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.argmax.html#numpy-argmax)\n",
    "* Do read the code in `src/qudi/logic/scanning_excitation_logic.py` and `src/qudi/hardware/tutorial/process_control.py` to understand how to use them! There are things like `acquisition_running` and `get_spectrum` that should catch your eye.\n",
    "* Remember to restart the jupyter kernel each time you restart Qudi.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Configuration solution\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "````{solution} level1\n",
    ":label: level1-solution-a\n",
    ":class: dropdown\n",
    "\n",
    "You can start the scan and wait for completion like this:\n",
    "```{code-block} yaml\n",
    "global:\n",
    "    # list of modules to load when starting\n",
    "    # startup_modules: ['time_series_gui']\n",
    "    startup_modules: []\n",
    "    # Server port for serving the active qudi module namespace locally (localhost).\n",
    "    # Used by e.g. the Qudi jupyter kernel.\n",
    "    namespace_server_port: 18861\n",
    "    # Save data to daily data sub-directories by default\n",
    "    daily_data_dirs: True\n",
    "    force_remote_calls_by_value: True\n",
    "gui:\n",
    "    time_series_gui:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'time_series.time_series_gui.TimeSeriesGui'\n",
    "        options:\n",
    "            use_antialias: True  # optional, set to False if you encounter performance issues\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            _time_series_logic_con: time_series_reader_logic\n",
    "    excitation_scanner_gui:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'excitation_scanner.excitation_gui.ScanningExcitationGui'\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            excitation_logic: excitation_scanner_logic\n",
    "logic:\n",
    "    time_series_reader_logic:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'time_series_reader_logic.TimeSeriesReaderLogic'\n",
    "        options:\n",
    "            max_frame_rate: 20  # optional (default: 20Hz)\n",
    "            channel_buffer_size: 1048576  # optional (default: 1MSample)\n",
    "            max_raw_data_bytes: 1073741824  # optional (default: 1GB)\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            streamer: process_control_time_series\n",
    "    excitation_scanner_logic:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'scanning_excitation_spectroscopy.ScanningExcitationLogic'\n",
    "        options:\n",
    "            beep: True # default\n",
    "            watchdog_repeat_time_ms: 500 # default\n",
    "            save_idle_to_global_metadata: True # save the current idle value to global metadata\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            scanner: excitation_scanner_hardware\n",
    "    frequency_optimize_logic:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'frequency_optimize.FrequencyOptimizeLogic'\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            scanner_logic: excitation_scanner_logic\n",
    "            process_hardware: process_control\n",
    "hardware:\n",
    "    excitation_scanner_hardware:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'tutorial.laser.ExcitationScannerTutorial'\n",
    "    process_control:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'tutorial.process_control.ProcessControlTutorial'\n",
    "    process_control_time_series:\n",
    "        module.Class: 'interfuse.process_value_to_datainstream_interfuse.ProcessDataStream'\n",
    "        connect:\n",
    "            process: process_control\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "````\n",
    "\n",
    "### Partial solution for step 1.\n",
    "\n",
    "````{solution} level1\n",
    ":label: level1-solution-b\n",
    ":class: dropdown\n",
    "\n",
    "You can start the scan and wait for completion like this:\n",
    "```{code-block} python\n",
    "self._scanner().set_variable(\"Start frequency\", fstart)\n",
    "self._scanner().set_variable(\"Stop frequency\", fstop)\n",
    "self._scanner().set_variable(\"Step frequency\", fstep)\n",
    "self._scanner().get_spectrum()\n",
    "# wait for the spectrum to finish\n",
    "while self._scanner().acquisition_running:\n",
    "    time.sleep(0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "````\n",
    "\n",
    "### Partial solution for step 2.\n",
    "\n",
    "````{solution} level1\n",
    ":label: level1-solution-c\n",
    ":class: dropdown\n",
    "\n",
    "You can find thecentral frequency and FWHM like this:\n",
    "```{code-block} python\n",
    "spectrum = self._scanner().spectrum\n",
    "frequency = self._scanner().frequency\n",
    "bg = np.quantile(spectrum, 0.1)\n",
    "imaxi = np.argmax(spectrum)\n",
    "amplitude = spectrum[imaxi] - bg\n",
    "f0 = frequency[imaxi]\n",
    "istart = np.nonzero(np.logical_and(spectrum - bg < amplitude/2, frequency < f0))[0][-1]\n",
    "istop = np.nonzero(np.logical_and(spectrum - bg < amplitude/2, frequency > f0))[0][0]\n",
    "fstart = frequency[istart]\n",
    "fstop = frequency[istop]\n",
    "fwhm = abs(fstop - fstart)\n",
    "```\n",
    "````\n",
    "\n",
    "### Partial solution for step 3 and 4.\n",
    "\n",
    "````{solution} level1\n",
    ":label: level1-solution-d\n",
    ":class: dropdown\n",
    "\n",
    "You can start the scan and wait for completion like this:\n",
    "```{code-block} python\n",
    "# 3. Manually scan the frequencies\n",
    "scanned_setpoints = np.linspace(f0-6*fwhm, f0+6*fwhm, 100)\n",
    "fluorescence = np.zeros_like(scanned_setpoints)\n",
    "for (i,f) in enumerate(scanned_setpoints):\n",
    "    self._scanner().idle = f\n",
    "    time.sleep(0.1)\n",
    "    fluorescence[i] = self._process().get_process_value(\"APD\")\n",
    "    imax = np.argmax(fluorescence)\n",
    "# 4. Go there\n",
    "self._scanner().idle = scanned_setpoints[imax]\n",
    "```\n",
    "````\n",
    "\n",
    "### Complete solution\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "````{solution} level1\n",
    ":label: level1-solution-e\n",
    ":class: dropdown\n",
    "\n",
    "You can start the scan and wait for completion like this:\n",
    "```{code-block} python\n",
    "import time\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "from qudi.core.connector import Connector\n",
    "from qudi.core.module import LogicBase\n",
    "from qudi.interface.process_control_interface import ProcessValueInterface\n",
    "from qudi.logic.scanning_excitation_spectroscopy import ScanningExcitationLogic\n",
    "\n",
    "class FrequencyOptimizeLogic(LogicBase):\n",
    "    _scanner = Connector(name='scanner_logic', interface=ScanningExcitationLogic)\n",
    "    _process = Connector(name='process_hardware', interface=ProcessValueInterface)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def on_activate(self):\n",
    "        # do you need something here? -> no!\n",
    "        pass\n",
    "\n",
    "    def on_deactivate(self):\n",
    "        # do you need something here? -> no!\n",
    "        pass\n",
    "\n",
    "    def optimize_frequency(self, fstart, fstop, fstep):\n",
    "        # 1. Scan the frequencies\n",
    "        self._scanner().set_variable(\"Start frequency\", fstart)\n",
    "        self._scanner().set_variable(\"Stop frequency\", fstop)\n",
    "        self._scanner().set_variable(\"Step frequency\", fstep)\n",
    "        self._scanner().get_spectrum()\n",
    "        # wait for the spectrum to finish\n",
    "        while self._scanner().acquisition_running:\n",
    "            time.sleep(0.5)\n",
    "        # 2. get the data and find the maximum\n",
    "        spectrum = self._scanner().spectrum\n",
    "        frequency = self._scanner().frequency\n",
    "        bg = np.quantile(spectrum, 0.1)\n",
    "        imaxi = np.argmax(spectrum)\n",
    "        amplitude = spectrum[imaxi] - bg\n",
    "        f0 = frequency[imaxi]\n",
    "        istart = np.nonzero(np.logical_and(spectrum - bg < amplitude/2, frequency < f0))[0][-1]\n",
    "        istop = np.nonzero(np.logical_and(spectrum - bg < amplitude/2, frequency > f0))[0][0]\n",
    "        fstart = frequency[istart]\n",
    "        fstop = frequency[istop]\n",
    "        fwhm = abs(fstop - fstart)\n",
    "        # 3. Manually scan the frequencies\n",
    "        scanned_setpoints = np.linspace(f0-6*fwhm, f0+6*fwhm, 100)\n",
    "        fluorescence = np.zeros_like(scanned_setpoints)\n",
    "        for (i,f) in enumerate(scanned_setpoints):\n",
    "            self._scanner().idle = f\n",
    "            time.sleep(0.1)\n",
    "            fluorescence[i] = self._process().get_process_value(\"APD\")\n",
    "        imax = np.argmax(fluorescence)\n",
    "        # 4. Go there\n",
    "        self._scanner().idle = scanned_setpoints[imax]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "````"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8c6b0cef-25d3-4937-9630-182bc5727566",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Level 2: What data can I find from my neighbor's computer?\n",
    "\n",
    "Try to modify your configuration and the code of the logic to be able to use hardwares that are on another computer!"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2b9901f0-ad9c-4a3e-8c53-7b8745b2b92f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# The modules we commonly use\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section we are going to go through some common modules, especially user interfaces, that we use for single molecule applications. Please load the `default.cfg` configuration and restart Qudi. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3725acb0-0d16-4ea9-897a-e38b3832440c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The time series GUI\n",
    "\n",
    "The GUI that we have been using the most during this lecture is the time series GUI. It is rather simple, reliable, and always useful. It is worth describing a bit some of its functionalities. This GUI and the corresponding `TimeSeriesReaderLogic` deal with hardwares implementing the `DataInStreamInterface`. They also calculate moving averages of the acquired signals.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/time_series_illustration.svg\n",
    ":width: 100%\n",
    "\n",
    "The main time series window. Your (mostly) reliable best friend.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c0f0b33b-84df-4951-bc5f-d5e2ff6411ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Going from left to right and top to bottom in the previous figure, we have:\n",
    "* The start/stop button, that... starts and stop the acquisition,\n",
    "* The start/stop recording data, that will start recording a running acquisition for as long as you want,\n",
    "* The take snapshot button. Did you see something interesting in the data trace but forgot to start the acquisition? quick! press this button!\n",
    "* The freeze autoscaling of the Y axis button. This is an addition we made to the original Ulm IQO GUI to tame a bit the autoscaling. It is useful for example in situations where you are aligning on a weak signal, but have some strong signals that can come and parasite the data trace.\n",
    "* The trace view selection and channel settings buttons, that open the corresponding setting windows that we detail below.\n",
    "* The curent value channel combo box, that controls which measured value is being displayed.\n",
    "* The trace length spin box, which controls how long the stored data are.\n",
    "* The data rate spin box, which controls the data rate of the trace being displayed.\n",
    "* The oversampling factor, which controls how much faster the hardware is acquiring data.\n",
    "* The moving average width, which controls how many data points are used for calculating moving averages."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e1e2d66e-f8f7-431b-8be3-531b55089b61",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are two important control points that can be called using the trace view selection and channel settings buttons. The first one is the trace view window. It only controls what is being **displayed** in the window. The data that are hidden are still being acquired and will be saved to file if you request that.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/trace_view_selection.png\n",
    ":width: 40%\n",
    "\n",
    "The trace view window.\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "The second control point is the channel settings window. It controls what data are actually being acquired. It is not accessible when data acquisition is running.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/data_channel_settings.png\n",
    ":width: 40%\n",
    "\n",
    "The channel settings window.\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "```{note}\n",
    "When performing alignement, it is sometimes useful to disable moving average acquisition. Indeed, calculating the moving average introduces a temporal lag in what is being displayed which can be annoying when aligning.\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "For an example of how to set-up the time series reader, please refer to [the guide on time series](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/iqo-docs/setup_timeseries.html)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3aede790-d9ac-4192-b21e-a30ef56b7955",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The scanner GUI: running confocal scans and controlling the galvo mirror\n",
    "\n",
    "If you do confocal microscopy, this setup is very useful. It allows scanning the sample plane in as many dimensions as are available and optimizing on punctual sources.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/scanner_gui_annotated.svg\n",
    ":width: 100%\n",
    "\n",
    "The Scanner GUI. Available axes may vary.\n",
    "```\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6c8c4712-2866-4776-bbff-50ac64f22c9f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This window includes many features. You can scan pairs of axes, or axes alone. You can navigate through the history of scans (this will also move the cursor to the saved position). Finally, you can also move the position manually and use the automatic optimization feature to get the best position on a punctual emitter. Some notes on the features:\n",
    "\n",
    "* You can add tags to the saved file names,\n",
    "* The amplitude of the movements of the cursor (the green cross) depends on the level of zoom. If you want to perform precise movements, zoom-in!\n",
    "* There is a tilt-correction feature where you specify three points that you know for sure are in focus, and the logic tries to correct the movements so that planar movements are parallel to the sample surface.\n",
    "* The optimizer is very useful, and also very dumb. I will fit 2D or 1D Gaussians successively and go to the maximum, whatever the result of the fit is. This means that when you work in low signal situations, you are at risk of losing your position. Be ready to jump on the stop button before it goes crazy!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "851adf9b-5f4f-4b7a-9c4c-caafab9e0d7d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If you are interested in setting up confocal scanning, have a look at [the guide on confocal scanning](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/iqo-docs/setup_confocal_scanning.html)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8fa4fb94-c11a-4ac5-a53f-6503d333d7c6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The National Instruments hardwares and their configurations\n",
    "\n",
    "One of the best handled piece of hardware in Qudi are the National Instruments DAQ cards. This is probably due to historical reasons and their widespread use in fields doing confocal micrsocopy. There are no less than 4 hardware modules that can deal with them. Some notes:\n",
    "* The [NIXSeriesFiniteSamplingIO](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/hardware/NationalInstruments/ni_x_series_analog_output.html) hardware is one of the simplest. It does not handle any timing, and allows you to control analog outputs on-the-go. This is typically what you manipulate through the cursor of the confocal scanner, some setpoints for the lasers, etc.\n",
    "* The [NIXSeriesInStreamer](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/hardware/NationalInstruments/ni_x_series_in_streamer.html) implements the [DataInStreamInterface](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/data_instream_interface.html). This is typically what you will plug into the [TimeSeriesReaderLogic](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/logic/time_series_reader_logic.html).\n",
    "* The [NIXSeriesFiniteSamplingIO](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/hardware/NationalInstruments/ni_x_series_finite_sampling_io.html) implements the [`FiniteSamplingIOInterface`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/finite_sampling_io_interface.html), which we did not cover. Its role is to acquire and/or output a finite number of analog and/or digital values with a precise timing. This is typically what you will use to acquire a scan with the confocal scanner or with the laser excitation scanners. You can also use one of it's output to synchronize other acquisition hardwares (for example, and EMCCD camera!).\n",
    "* The [NIXSeriesFiniteSamplingInput](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/hardware/NationalInstruments/ni_x_series_finite_sampling_input.html) implements the [`FiniteSamplingInputInterface`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/finite_sampling_input_interface.html), which we did not cover. It is a restricted version of the previous hardware, dealing only with input. As much as it is possible, I recommend against using it, as it will interfere with the time series if both are running at the same time.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6212f537-ff9d-4a78-bf8b-3508e1c358f2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Laser scanners\n",
    "\n",
    "The excitation spectroscopy setup is something we developped internally in the group. It revolves around the [Excitationscanner interface](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/excitation_scanner_interface.html), the [Scanning Excitation Logic](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/logic/scanning_excitation_spectroscopy.html), and the [Scanning excitation spectroscopy GUI](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/gui/scanning_excitation_spectroscopy.html)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "321b0462-204f-45ee-bc1a-5396ddd07c43",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### The laser scanner user interface\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/laser_window_annotated.svg\n",
    ":width: 100%\n",
    "\n",
    "The laser scanner user interface\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b6fbf32e-8bbd-42bd-ac00-c25e1703c15f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Because each laser and acquisition system has its own specificities for how we control and scan the frequencies, the logic and the GUI are very generalistic. This reflects in the control part of the GUI where we separate the common settings (exposure time, number of repetitions, and the scanner status), and the laser-specific part. In my screenshot we have the specific controls for the 785nm dfb laser, that we control by sending an analog voltage for the setpoint of its temperature PID. There is also a section to write free-form textual notes that are useful to keep track of some other experimental parameters.\n",
    "\n",
    "The second half of the window is dedicated to data exploration and control of the laser frequency. After a scan has been run, you can select a fit region either by entering manually the region boundaries, or by drag-and-dropping the yellow boundaries in the plot. If the displayed fit region becomes cumbersome, you can also hide it. You can also select which repetition number to fit (it starts at 0). The fit models available are in the drop-down menu in the highlighted blue region. Other models are available and can be added using the fit coniguration window. You can open it from the {kbd}`View > Show Fit Settings` menu.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/fit_configuration.png\n",
    ":width: 70%\n",
    "\n",
    "The fit configuration window\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, you can control the current frequency of the laser through 3 different inputs.\n",
    "1. By directly inputing a number in the `X` input of the `Target` group,\n",
    "2. By drag-and-dropping the green cursor in the plot,\n",
    "3. Using the cursor at the very bottom. This also supports mousewheel interactions when the mouse hovers it. The displacement amount of one step of the mousewheel is given by the full available scan range divided by the `Scroll step divider`. In the screenshot above, since the full available range is roughly 260GHz, and because the divider is $10^{3}$, this means one step is 260MHz.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{warning}\n",
    "For the laser frequency control to work, you need to have the `Laser follow cursor` switch enabled.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f45eecff-d299-4f24-82b8-84812b756dea",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### The laser scanner logic\n",
    "\n",
    "The [Scanning Excitation Logic](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/logic/scanning_excitation_spectroscopy.html) is responsible for driving the scan hardwares on a high-level view. It can be used to start and stop scans, setting scan parameters, laser frequency, fitting, and saving the data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a1dfff34-5777-44e5-86f2-0823a916a599",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Hardwares\n",
    "\n",
    "We have hardware implemented foreach of our lasers. Depending on the laser capabilities (or the manufacturer good will to document them), the acquisition method is different. There roughly two methods:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Lasers for which we are able to synchronize the scanning timing with the reading of the detector. They typically use a [`FiniteSamplingIOInterface`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/finite_sampling_io_interface.html) for acquisition _and_ control,\n",
    "2. Lasers for which we can't do that. In these cases, we typically use the finite sampling for acquisition, start the scanning and the acquisition at the same time, and sample the frequency from time to time during the scan to interpolate it a posteriori. This is obviously less reliable since it uses the timing of the computer (and even the network!) to sample the frequency."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1f273170-b98c-4800-bb0c-0dba76fd6c93",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### State machines\n",
    "\n",
    "Although this is not a requirement to implement a hardware for the laser scanner logic, I've found it useful to use a finite state machine design pattern. This is done using the [`SampledFiniteStateInterface`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/sampled_finite_state_interface.html), check its documentation if you are curious. An example finite state machine is the dummy hardware `ExcitationScannerDummy`, whose finite state machine is depicted below. You can also get inspiration from it to implement your own hardwares.\n",
    "```{figure} ./crash_course_sources/qudi.hardware.dummy.excitation_scanner_dummy.ExcitationScannerDummy.svg\n",
    ":width: 60%\n",
    "\n",
    "The state machine of the dummy laser. On the right the simplified version without the interuption routines.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bf0c8d3b-8c82-4ab9-9d61-aa6aae7fe7e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As you can see, the state machine is quite simple once you remove the transitions corresponding to scan interruption. It is also quite representative of the other state machines for the rel lasers. Typically, you have\n",
    "* a `prepare idle` and an `idle` states whose job is just to set the frequency when we are not scanning (typically to go in resonance with a molecule),\n",
    "* a `prepare scan` state, which allocates the buffers in wich we will store the data, and prepares the hardware,\n",
    "* a `prepare step` state, which prepares the hardware to perform one repetition of the scan and stops the scan once all repetitions have been made,\n",
    "* a `wait ready` state, which waits for the hardware to be ready to scan,\n",
    "* and a `record scan step` state, which stores the acquired data in the buffers.\n",
    "\n",
    "This states are typically displayed in the scanning excitation GUI."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a672e524-5768-4966-a2b7-0d93dc439075",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Finite sampling excitation interfuse\n",
    "\n",
    "We use the [`FiniteSamplingScanningExcitationInterfuse`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/hardware/excitation_scanners/finite_sampling_scanning_excitation.html) hardware to control the 785nm DFB laser. As you can see this is a \"good\" laser, and it reflects in the simplicity of its state machine:\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} ./crash_course_sources/qudi.hardware.interfuse.finite_sampling_scanning_excitation.FiniteSamplingScanningExcitationInterfuse.svg\n",
    ":width: 60%\n",
    "\n",
    "The state machine for the finite sampling scanning excitation interfuse. On the right, the simplified version with the interuption transition and the stopped state removed.\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "```{note}\n",
    "An interfuse is a qudi-specific term to call a hardware that fuses together one or several hardware to provide a new interface implementation. \n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Optionally, this hardware is able to control a [`ProcessSetpointInterface`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/process_control_interface.html), which value will be update every few scan repetitions. The typical use would be changing the temperature of a cryostat, or the power of a laser, every few scan repetition. Right now the way to do it is a bit clunky, I hope we can make it easier in the future, and/or move this to the logic rather than the hardware. When an external process setpoint is configured, \n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/external_setpoint_scanner.jpg\n",
    ":width: 60%\n",
    "\n",
    "The control variables with an external process setpoint configured. Here a cryostat.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1a0de091-43db-44c8-a9e8-a625ec8ef1e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "When `External  enabled` is ticked, the hardware will set the external process setpoint to `First external setpoint` (20K), and change the setpoint every three scans. This means that the temperature step will be 12K, to reach 32K. the `External setpoint repeat per step` and `External setpoint step` settings are linked to the number of repetitions you set. **Check that these values correspond to what you want to do before running scans!** There is also an additional waiting time that lets the external process stabilize after changing the setpoint before scanning the frequencies.\n",
    "\n",
    "Optionally, the hardware is able to read a [`ProcessValueInterface`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/process_control_interface.html) to read its value at the beginning and at the end of each step. The intermediary values (during the acquisition) are automatically interpolated."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "02114d3d-9861-466a-b1c6-5152c1123e4a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##### Laser specifics: DFB laser\n",
    "\n",
    "The example taken above is for the DFB laser and the cryostat. In the lab, we have two pre-configured hardwares. One where we speak to the cryostat, and another where we don't. When we connect to the cryostat, we use the sepoint to set the temperature, and the temperature value for the stored process value.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/5d3c2a5f-415a-40ae-bd7e-aa280971513f.png\n",
    ":width: 60%\n",
    "\n",
    "The DFB can have an external control hardware connected. For simplicity in Lab 66 we have two corresponding configurations available\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "If you want to use the setup with the cryo, don't forget to enable external controls in the Cryostation software to allow Qudi to connect!\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/ce06e35a-71d8-420d-88bb-e134a2f325f7.png\n",
    ":width: 60%\n",
    "\n",
    "Don't forget to click on {kbd}`ENABLE EXTERNAL CONTROL` in the Cryostation software if you are using the dfb with the cryo. \n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6f9158cb-90e6-4129-9f5f-75ae33117178",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### A slightly more complicated example: the Moglabs CEM laser\n",
    "\n",
    "We can use the Moglabs Cat-Eye motorised laser to perform excitation spectroscopy. This laser is extermely capricious, but is somewhat usable to do short scans up to a few GHz in range. Its state machine is given below:\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/qudi.hardware.interfuse.moglabs_scanning_excitation.FiniteSamplingScanningExcitationInterfuse.svg\n",
    ":width: 60%\n",
    "\n",
    "The state machine for the Moglabls CEM laser. On the right, the simplified version with the interruption transitions and the stopped state removed.\n",
    "```\n",
    "As you can see there are additional states corresponding to idling scans. This is because the laser tends to be not reliable when not performing scans, so it is often better to keep it scanning. Importantly, the idle controls that you would use with other lasers do not work with the Moglabs. Instead, it is better to use the scan controls while performing idle scans. This may change in the future if I get time to work on it.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/moglabs_control_variables\n",
    ":width: 30%\n",
    "\n",
    "The control variables available with the Moglabs.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f4107c3e-641d-49b2-9ab2-862eef1c3e1d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This laser comprises three elements:\n",
    "1. The cavity itself, that lets you control the position of the grating in steps. Values allowing lasing are in the range ~9000 to ~13000.\n",
    "2. The laser driver, that controls the position of the internal piezo of the cavity, as well as the current of the diode. You can control the setpoint of the current, and the ramp sent to the piezo for scanning through its offset and span. You can also control the duty cycle of the ramp: a 0.5 duty cycle is a symetric triangular wave, while a 0.0 duty cycle is a ramp with an abrupt change at the end. Finally, the laser driver alsomodulates a bit the current offset with the ramp. This is controlled with the bias setting.\n",
    "3. The last element is the Fizeau wavemeter. This element has almost been well designed by the manufacturer, as it has a trigger input and is able to store measurements in its internal buffer. Unfortunately, the trigger does notwork with an edge, but instead with a constant level signal. This makes it difficult to trigger it using a standard TTL clock, as it will trigger several times for a single clock cycle depending on its (automatically set) internal exposure time. This forces us to probe directly the wavemeter with the computer at (hopefully, remember that a computer is usually bad at timing) regular intervals and then interpolate the frequencies at the end of a scan step. The fizeau probing rate is given by the `fzw probe rate` setting. Too fast, and the computer cannot keep-up, resulting in wrong frequency interpolation. Too slow, and you will miss important informations such as mode jumps."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e1a3fc11-a3ac-457c-b71b-2c64106e4221",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### A more complicated example: the Matisse laser\n",
    "\n",
    "We control our Matisse laser through three hardwares. Two of them run on the computer dedicated to this laser:\n",
    "1. The High Finesse wavemeter, controlled by the [`HighFinesseWavemeter`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/hardware/wavemeter/high_finesse_wavemeter.html) hardware,\n",
    "2. The Matisse Proxy, controlled by the [`MatisseProxy`](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/hardware/excitation_scanners/matisse.html) hardware, which serves as an intermediary between the Matisse software and Qudi.\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, on the main computer, we have a hardware that implements the [Excitationscanner interface](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/interface/excitation_scanner_interface.html). Like the others it has a finite state machine, shown below.\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} crash_course_sources/qudi.hardware.interfuse.remote_matisse_scanner.RemoteMatisseScanner.svg\n",
    ":width: 60%\n",
    "\n",
    "The state machine for the Matisse laser. On the right, the simplified version where the interruption transitions and the stopped state have been removed.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "537dd73d-67ab-48cf-86bc-2987acd11272",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It has an additional `prepare stitch` and `go to position` states that are used to perform stitches. The `go to position` method is implemented directly in the `MatisseProxy` module. If you want to get crazy, have a look at its [state machine](https://lab-on-a-molecule-quantum-nanophotonics.github.io/qudi-lab-on-a-molecule-modules/modules/hardware/excitation_scanners/matisse.html#matisse-proxy)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "823922f3-8921-4299-ac0e-a06f712d48c2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Pulsers\n",
    "\n",
    "Unfortunately, I haven't experimented too much with those yet. This is also a part that is being actively developped at IQO, so it might change in the future. However, I can give a brief overview or things that are currently possible."
   ]
  },
  {
